Done. Added the **Charles L. Brown Wreck** (Sint Eustatius) to `src/data/sites.json` and pushed to main.

**Why this pick:** Among my Americas-Atlantic region, the `statia-st-eustatius` location had **zero** sites, and National Geographic calls Statia "the best place to dive in the Caribbean." The Charles L. Brown is its flagship dive — a 100 m (327 ft) former AT&T cable-layer (built 1954 as *CS Salernum*), scuttled in 2003, and rated "Premier Wreck Dive in the Caribbean" by Sport Diver. The coverage-gaps file was largely stale (Molinere, RMS Rhone, MV Captain Keith Tibbetts, Karpata are all already covered) and its remaining gaps point at countries with no matching location entry (Canada, Aruba, Turks & Caicos, etc.).

**Facts verified** across PADI, Scuba Diving magazine, and dive-site databases: built 1954 Naples, sunk 25 Jul 2003, lies on her side off the leeward SW coast, top ~20 m / bottom ~30 m, ~100 m long, resident barracuda "Charlie," horse-eye jacks, cubera snapper, reef sharks. Coordinates from PADI (17.4626, -62.9902), conditions calibrated to the NE-Caribbean profile.

**Hero image:** set to `null`. I searched Wikimedia Commons under the site name, the ship's original name (*CS Salernum*), "Charlie Brown," and the *Sint Eustatius National Marine Park* category — that category holds only a location map and an ISS satellite photo, with no underwater or wreck imagery anywhere on Commons. Per the rules, a null beats putting a generic reef shot on a wreck card.

Sources: [Scuba Diving — Charlie Brown](https://www.scubadiving.com/keywords/underwater-photography/secret-dive-spot-beast-steel-sint-eustatius), [PADI dive site](https://www.padi.com/dive-site/sint-eustatius/charles-l-brown/), [National Geographic](https://www.nationalgeographic.com/travel/article/this-tiny-island-is-best-place-to-dive-in-caribbean)

